        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat: add Chutes provider for usage/quota tracking",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nAdd Chutes provider for usage/quota tracking\n\n## Why this matters\n\nThe issue requests adding Chutes (chutes.ai) as a CodexBar provider so users on a Chutes subscription can see their usage/quota in the menu bar. The issue is labeled `accepted`, `enhancement`, `area:providers`, which are the maintainer-triaged greenlight labels used for the provider lane on this repo. A contributor (Yuxin-Qiao) researched the public docs and identified the relevant authenticated endpoints: `GET /users/me/subscription_usage` (monthly usage/caps plus a 4-hour rolling window when a subscription is active), `GET /users/me/quotas`, and `GET /users/me/quota_usage/{chute_id}`. There is no in-flight PR and no claim on the issue. Chutes uses an API-key auth model, which maps directly onto CodexBar's existing `api` fetch strategy.\n\n## Changes\n\nFollow the established API-token provider template, using the Synthetic provider (\"API key from config/env -> quota API\", `api` strategy) as the closest analog. Add a `chutes` case to the `UsageProvider` enum in `Sources/CodexBarCore/Providers/Providers.swift` (both occurrences). Create `Sources/CodexBarCore/Providers/Chutes/` with a descriptor (`ChutesProviderDescriptor`), a usage-stats/fetcher type that calls `GET /users/me/subscription_usage` with the configured API key and maps the response into the shared `UsageSnapshot`/`RateWindow` model, and a settings reader for the token. Create `Sources/CodexBar/Providers/Chutes/` with `ChutesProviderImplementation` and `ChutesSettingsStore`. Wire the implementation into `ProviderImplementationRegistry.makeImplementation(for:)` (the `case .synthetic:` switch) and register the descriptor in `ProviderDescriptor.descriptorsByID`. Add a provider SVG icon, a `docs/providers.md` table row, and a `ChutesProviderTests.swift` that exercises the fetcher against a stubbed transport using `ProviderHTTPTransportStub`. Because the public OpenAPI does not pin exact field names, the fetcher should parse defensively (optional decoding with fallbacks) and surface a clear \"no usage data\" state rather than crashing on a shape mismatch.\n\n## Testing\n\n- Happy path: `subscription_usage` returns active subscription with monthly cap + 4h rolling window; fetcher maps to a populated `UsageSnapshot` with correct used/limit and reset timing.\n- Edge case: no active subscription (free/quota-only account) -> fetcher falls back to `quotas` shape or returns a benign empty/\"no subscription\" snapshot, no crash.\n- Edge case: response JSON missing expected fields -> defensive optional decoding yields a clear no-data state, not a decode error.\n- Error path: missing/invalid API key -> 401/403 surfaces as an auth error in the provider card, consistent with other `api` providers.\n- Registry wiring: provider appears in `ProviderDescriptor.all` and resolves to a `ChutesProviderImplementation` via the registry (mirrors existing provider-registry test coverage).\n\nFixes #176\n\nAI was used for assistance.\n",
        "branch": "fix/176-codexbar-chutes-provider",
